    <div class="mb-5 md:mb-7">
      <h2 class="text-brand text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-1">
        What Makes a Good Xbox Gamertag?
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        You have got hundreds of name ideas in front of you — but how do you know which one is actually good? Not just available, but something you would be proud to drop into a Warzone lobby or put on your Twitch overlay.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-dark-heading text-base md:text-lg font-bold leading-snug mb-1">The 4 Pillars of a Great Gamertag</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-3 pl-5 list-disc mb-5">
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Memorability</strong> — If someone plays one match with you and still remembers your tag later, that is a win. Short, punchy names tend to stick. Think FrostByte or PixelJunkie — simple but sharp.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Uniqueness</strong> — Numbers-for-letters might have been edgy in 2010 but now it just screams every name I wanted was taken. Go for something that stands out without trying too hard.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Brandability</strong> — Your gamertag is more than a name — it is your personal brand. Especially if you plan to stream, compete, or flex on leaderboards, choose something you could use across Xbox, Discord, Twitch, and beyond.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Relevance and Personal Connection</strong> — The best names reflect you. Whether it is a favourite game, personality trait, or aesthetic — pick something meaningful. You will enjoy using it more.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="text-dark-heading text-base md:text-lg font-bold leading-snug mb-1">Naming Rules You Actually Have to Follow</h3>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-3">
        Microsoft does have rules. Here is the quick version:
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-2 pl-5 list-disc mb-4">
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">Max of 12 characters excluding the suffix</li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">No offensive or copyrighted terms</li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">No impersonation or spammy symbols</li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">No trailing spaces or unusual punctuation</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-3">
        Keep it short, clean, and you. If it feels like something you would say out loud without cringing, you are on the right track.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        Want the full breakdown? We have a guide on <a href="#" class="text-brand underline underline-offset-2 font-semibold hover:text-brand-light transition-colors">Xbox Gamertag Naming Rules &amp; Guidelines You Must Follow</a> if you are the read-everything-twice type. And if you are still not sure what makes a name good, this deeper dive on <a href="#" class="text-brand underline underline-offset-2 font-semibold hover:text-brand-light transition-colors">What Makes a Good Gamertag</a> is worth a click.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- H2: How Do I Create a Unique Xbox Gamertag? -->
    <div class="mb-5 md:mb-7">
      <h2 class="text-brand text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-1">
        How Do I Create a Unique Xbox Gamertag?
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Coming up with a unique gamertag does not require magic — just a few solid tricks and a bit of personality.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-dark-heading text-base md:text-lg font-bold leading-snug mb-1">Quick Tips to Craft Something Original</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-3 pl-5 list-disc mb-5">
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Mash up two words</strong> — Mix your favourite things. Ninja + Bakery? Ninjabread. Weirdly awesome.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Pull from your favourite games or characters</strong> — Dig into lore, nicknames, or obscure side characters. Just avoid straight-up using famous character names.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Use alliteration or internal rhyming</strong> — Names like PixelPunk or LootLlama roll off the tongue and stick in people's heads.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Keep it short and brandable</strong> — The best tags are under 12 characters, easy to pronounce, and do not rely on numbers or symbols to be cool.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Be cross-platform ready</strong> — If it sounds good on Xbox and also fits your Twitch or Discord identity, you are set.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Thanks to Microsoft's modern gamertag system, you can now grab popular names with a suffix like #1234. So if GhostBlade is taken, you might still get it — with a unique code behind the scenes that is invisible most of the time.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        We have a full guide on <a href="#" class="text-brand underline underline-offset-2 font-semibold hover:text-brand-light transition-colors">How to Create a Unique Xbox Gamertag</a> that is packed with strategy — and if you want to dodge the biggest mistakes, definitely check out <a href="#" class="text-brand underline underline-offset-2 font-semibold hover:text-brand-light transition-colors">5 Naming Mistakes Xbox Players Still Make</a>. Be you — but the memorable version.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- H2: How to Claim Your New Gamertag -->
    <div class="mb-5 md:mb-7">
      <h2 class="text-brand text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-1">
        How to Claim Your New Gamertag
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Found the one? Claim it before someone else does. Gamertags are first-come, first-served even with the suffix system — so if it feels right, lock it in.
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-2 pl-5 list-disc mb-4">
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">On Xbox Console</strong> — Go to your profile, select Customize profile, then Gamertag, and enter your new name.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">On PC via Xbox App</strong> — Click your profile icon, go to Settings, then Gamertag, and update it.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">On the Web</strong> — Visit your Microsoft account settings and change it from there.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-3">
        Your first gamertag change is free — after that, Microsoft charges a small fee. So make this one count.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        If you need a full step-by-step guide, head over to our walkthrough on <a href="#" class="text-brand underline underline-offset-2 font-semibold hover:text-brand-light transition-colors">how to change your Xbox gamertag</a> — complete with tips to avoid messing it up. Once you have claimed it, test it across Xbox, Discord, Twitch, and anywhere else you hang out.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- H2: Will Microsoft Release Old Gamertags Again? -->
    <div class="mb-5 ">
      <h2 class="text-brand text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-1">
        Will Microsoft Release Old Gamertags Again?
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        For years, Xbox users hoped that old inactive gamertags would eventually get recycled and released back into the wild. And to be fair, that used to happen — Microsoft would occasionally free up abandoned tags tied to long-dead accounts.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        But those days are basically over. With the rollout of the modern gamertag system — the one that adds invisible suffixes like #1298 — Microsoft moved away from releasing inactive names. The reason is simple: now everyone can choose the name they want without taking it from someone who had it first.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        If you want the full breakdown, we have a guide on <a href="#" class="text-brand underline underline-offset-2 font-semibold hover:text-brand-light transition-colors">when (or if) the Xbox team will ever recycle old gamertags</a> that explains the whole policy shift in detail. Bottom line — if the name you want is taken, the suffix system gives you a second chance.
      </p>
    </div>

   
  </div>
</section>
